"# Chapter 2 — Exceptions

Sometimes something goes wrong. A lookup fails, an argument is out of
range, a file the caller thought existed doesn't. Motoi has two verbs
for saying so — `error` and `raise` — and one form for catching what
was raised — `guard`.

## Why exceptions exist

You could return a special value to signal failure — `#f`, or a
symbol like `'not-found`. That works until the special value is a
legitimate answer somewhere else in the program. Then callers can't
tell 'no result' from 'the result was #f'.

Exceptions separate the two. The normal return channel carries
answers; the exception channel carries failures. Callers who want to
handle failure reach for `guard` and see the failure; callers who
don't reach for `guard` and the failure walks all the way up until
someone does.

## Problem 1 — Say what went wrong

`error` raises an exception with a message and optional irritants.
`guard` catches it.

```
(define (safe-divide a b)
  (guard (c (#t 'divide-by-zero))
    (if (= b 0)
        (error \"cannot divide by zero\")
        (/ a b))))

(display (safe-divide 10 2))
;; => 5
(display (safe-divide 10 0))
;; => divide-by-zero
```

Read the `guard` shape. `(guard (c (test1 body1) (test2 body2) ...))`
means: run the body inside guard, and if it raises, bind the raised
value to `c` and try each `(test body)` clause. The first test that
returns truthy runs its body as the result. `#t` catches everything.

## Problem 2 — Look at what was raised

`error` builds an ERROR OBJECT that carries the message and any extra
irritants. You can inspect it with `error-object-message`,
`error-object-irritants`, and `error-object?`.

```
(guard (c ((error-object? c)
           (display \"caught: \")
           (display (error-object-message c))
           (display \"; irritants: \")
           (display (error-object-irritants c))))
  (error \"bad-arg\" 42 'expected-integer))
;; => caught: bad-arg; irritants: (42 expected-integer)
```

The message is a human-readable string. The irritants are the extra
values you passed to `error` — usually the offending inputs.

## Problem 3 — Discriminate two kinds of failure

The test in a guard clause can look at the raised value and choose to
handle it or re-raise. This lets you write handlers that catch only
what they know about.

```
(define (parse-positive-int s)
  (let ((n (string->number s)))
    (cond ((not n) (error \"not a number\" s))
          ((< n 0) (error \"negative\" n))
          (else n))))

(define (report x)
  (guard (c ((error-object? c)
             (cond ((equal? (error-object-message c) \"not a number\")
                    (display \"please type a number.\\n\"))
                   ((equal? (error-object-message c) \"negative\")
                    (display \"please type a positive number.\\n\"))
                   (else
                    (display \"unknown problem: \")
                    (display (error-object-message c))
                    (newline)))))
    (display (parse-positive-int x))
    (newline)))

(report \"42\")
;; => 42
(report \"cats\")
;; => please type a number.
(report \"-5\")
;; => please type a positive number.
```

The guard doesn't hide the failure — it names each failure and tells
the user what to do next. That is the shape of a program that fails
gracefully.

## Problem 4 (expert) — Raise a symbol, catch by identity

You don't have to raise an error object. `raise` takes ANY value.
This is useful for control flow — flagging an escape condition
without building a whole error.

```
(define (find-first-negative lst)
  (guard (c ((eq? c 'found-it) 'yes-negative))
    (for-each (lambda (x)
                (if (< x 0)
                    (raise 'found-it)
                    #f))
              lst)
    'no-negative))

(display (find-first-negative (list 1 2 3 -1 5)))
;; => yes-negative
(display (find-first-negative (list 1 2 3 4 5)))
;; => no-negative
```

`raise 'found-it` doesn't build an error object; it raises the SYMBOL
`found-it`. The guard clause `((eq? c 'found-it) 'yes-negative)`
catches exactly that symbol. This shape is called a NON-LOCAL EXIT —
we escaped the for-each loop the moment we found what we needed.

## Capstone — A calculator that survives typos

A tiny calculator that keeps running even if the user types garbage.

```
(define (calc a op b)
  (guard (c ((error-object? c) 'bad-input))
    (cond ((eq? op '+) (+ a b))
          ((eq? op '-) (- a b))
          ((eq? op '*) (* a b))
          ((eq? op '/) (if (= b 0)
                            (error \"divide-by-zero\")
                            (/ a b)))
          (else (error \"unknown op\" op)))))

(display (calc 10 '+ 3))
;; => 13
(display (calc 10 '/ 0))
;; => bad-input
(display (calc 10 'wat 3))
;; => bad-input
```

Notice the shape: normal answers flow out as numbers; abnormal
answers flow out as `'bad-input`. The caller can distinguish one
from the other without a single #f check.

## What's next

In Chapter 3 we get hash tables. Records tell us what a value is;
exceptions tell us what went wrong; hash tables let us look up
values by key. Three tools, one shape each, small enough to keep in
your head all at once.
")
